        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text> 
                        Potentia[e] Romanoru[m] prior Scipio viam aperuerat: luxuria[e] posterior aperuit. Quippe, remoto Carthaginis metu, sublataq[ue] 
                        imperij a[e]mul&acirc;; non gradu, sed pra[e]cipiti cursu &agrave; virtute descitum, ad vitia transcursum; vetus disciplina deserta, noua 
                        inducta; in somnum a vigiliis, ab armis ad voluptates, a negotijs in otium conuersa ciuitas. Tum Scipio Nasica in Capitolio porticus; 
                        tum illas circundatas duabus a[e]dibus Metellus; tum in circo Cn[aeus] Octavius mult&ograve; amenissimam moliti sunt: publicamq[ue] 
                        magnificentia[m] secuta priuata luxuria est. Paterculus l. 2. hist[oriae] Romana[e]. Partim Ciceronis elegantia[e]; partim Liuij uigori;
                        partim Sallustij breuitatis affinis.
                    </marginalia_text>
                <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                <person name="Publius Cornelius Scipio Nasica Corculum"/>
                <person name="Quintus Caecilius Metellus Macedonicus"/>
                <person name="Gnaeus Octavius"/> 
                <person name="Marcus Velleius Paterculus"/>
                <person name="Cicero"/>
                <person name="Livy"/>
                <person name="Sallust"/>
                <book title="Roman History"/>
                <location name="Rome"/>
                <location name="Carthage"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                “The first of the Scipios opened the way for the world power of the Romans; the second opened the way for luxury. For, when Rome was freed of 
                the fear of Carthage, and her rival in empire was out of her way, the path of virtue was abandoned for that of corruption, not gradually, but 
                in headlong course. The older discipline was discarded to give place to the new. The state passed from vigilance to slumber, from the pursuit 
                of arms to the pursuit of pleasure, from activity to idleness. It was at this time that there were built, on the Capitol, the porticoes of 
                Scipio Nasica, the porticoes of Metellus with the two temples placed around it, and, in the Circus, the portico of Gnaeus Octavius, the most 
                splendid of them all; and private luxury soon followed public extravagance.” Velleius Paterculus’ Roman history, bk. 2 [trans. Shipley]. 
                Partly similar to Cicero’s elegance, partly to Livy’s force, partly to Sallust’s concision.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
